"Romps D.M.","Response of tropical precipitation to global warming",2011,"Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences","68","1",,"123","138",,,10.1175/2010JAS3542.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79251491692&partnerID=40&md5=0cb5e5bcf0026650db98042a9bd12f7f","Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences, Harvard University, Cambridge, MA, United States","Romps, D.M., Department of Earth and Planetary Sciences, Harvard University, Cambridge, MA, United States","Using high-resolution cloud-resolving simulations with different CO2 concentrations, local precipitation fluxes are found to obey Clausius-Clapeyron (CC) scaling. Previous studies of the effect of CO2 concentration on precipitation extremes have used general circulation models, which are poor platforms for studying tropical convection because convection is parameterized. In idealized cloud-resolving simulations, it is possible to identify not only the changes in local precipitation fluxes, but also the factors responsible for those changes. There are many properties of convection that can change as the atmosphere warms, each of which could produce deviations from CC scaling. These properties include the effective watervapor gradient, cloud pressure depth, and cloud velocity. A simple theory is developed that predicts the changes in these properties consistent with CC scaling. Convection in the cloudresolving simulations is found to change as predicted by this theory, leading to an ~20% increase in local precipitation fluxes when the CO2 concentration is doubled. Overall, an increase in CO2 leads to more vigorous convection, composed of clouds that are wider, taller, and faster. © 2011 American Meteorological Society.","Carbon dioxide; Climate change; Cloud resolving models; Precipitation; Tropics","Cloud pressure; Cloud resolving models; Cloud velocity; Cloud-resolving simulation; Effect of CO; General circulation model; High resolution; Parameterized; Precipitation; Precipitation extremes; Precipitation fluxes; Tropical convection; Tropical precipitation; Carbon dioxide; Global warming; Tropics; Climate models; carbon dioxide; climate change; cloud microphysics; concentration (composition); convective cloud; general circulation model; global warming; precipitation (climatology); simulation; tropical meteorology",,,,,,"Allen, M.R., Ingram, W.J., Constraints on future changes in climate and the hydrologic cycle (2002) Nature, 419, pp. 224-232; Boer, G., Climate change and the regulation of the surface moisture and energy budgets (1993) Climate Dyn., 8, pp. 225-239; Bretherton, C., Challenges in numerical modeling of tropical circulations (2007) The Global Circulation of the Atmosphere, , T. Schneider and A. H. Sobel, Eds., Princeton University Press; Ciesielski, P.E., Johnson, R.H., Haertel, P.T., Wang, J., Corrected TOGA COARE sounding humidity data: Impact on diagnosed properties of convection and climate over the warm pool (2003) J. Climate, 16, pp. 2370-2384; Clough, S., Shephard, M., Mlawer, E., Delamere, J., Iacono, M., Cady-Pereira, K., Boukabara, S., Brown, P., Atmospheric radiative transfer modeling: A summary of the AER codes (2005) J. Quant. Spectrosc. Radiat. Transfer, 91, pp. 233-244; Commoner, B., (1971) The Closing Circle: Nature, Man, and Technology, p. 326. , Knopf; Del Genio, A.D., Yao, M.-S., Jonas, J., Will moist convection be stronger in a warmer climate? (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett., 34. , L16703, doi:10.1029/2007GL030525; Ehrlich, P.R., Holdren, J.P., A bulletin dialogue on ""The Closing Circle"": Critique (1972) Bull. At. Sci., 28, pp. 16-27; Emori, S., Brown, S.J., Dynamic and thermodynamic changes in mean and extreme precipitation under changed climate (2005) Geophys. Res. Lett., 32. , L17706, doi:10.1029/2005GL023272; Gordon, H., Whetton, P., Pittock, A., Fowler, A., Haylock, M., Simulated changes in daily rainfall intensity due to the enhanced greenhouse effect: Implications for extreme rainfall events (1992) Climate Dyn., 8, pp. 83-10